BriefingText:
BRIEFING

This lesson builds on Lesson 1, and takes you through the entire ascent. There are many systems involved, with up to five engines thrusting at the same time, producing up to 7,891,000 lbf (35,100 kN) of thrust.

The Apollo launch vehicle has three stages and 11 engines.

The first stage is named S-IC and is the initial booster stage. It has five engines and has the job of taking the spacecraft above the atmosphere. It will burn for about 168 seconds.
The second stage is named S-II and has the primary job of generating orbital speed and navigating the spacecraft into the correct trajectory. It also has five engines and will burn for 360 seconds.
The third stage is named S-IVB and has one engine. It's a multi start engine, and is designed to have two burns. One is the final part of ascent and into Earth Paring Orbit (EPO), and then the burn needed to reach the Moon (TLI, Trans-Lunar Injection).

Combined, the spacecraft is 363 feet (111 m) high. Most of the engines can be gimbaled and will automatically balance the launch vehicle during tower release. An Instrumentation Unit in the Launch Vehicle operates as the brain to automate most of the systems during ascent and guidance.

The LV will take you into the Earth Parking Orbit where the INSERTION checklist is performed.
Description: This lesson is all about how to ride and control the massive Saturn V launch vehicle, and its 7,891,000 lbf (35,100 kN) of thrust. I will teach you what to look for during the ascent, and what procedures to perform once the final stage engine cuts off and inserts you into orbit around Earth.

MissionCommands.Message: Welcome back into the Command Module cockpit and the Academy Lesson 2! This time we will test the checklist and what you learned in Lesson 1 before igniting those powerful F-1 engines and start the ascent,
Again, there are many systems involved so don't feel stressed if you don't yet understand what everything is, many of the steps involved is automatic unless something malfunctions.
The 363 feet (111 m) high Apollo rocket consists of three stages that will do the major work to get the spacecraft into orbit.
The first stage is named S-IC and is the initial booster stage. It has five engines and has the job of taking the spacecraft above the atmosphere. It will burn for about 168 seconds.
The second stage is named S-II and has the primary job of generating orbital speed and navigating the spacecraft into the correct trajectory. It also has five engines and will burn for 360 seconds.

The third stage is named S-IVB and has one engine. It's a multi start engine, and is designed to have two burns. One is the final part of ascent and into Earth Paring Orbit (EPO), and then the burn needed to reach the Moon (TLI, Trans-Lunar Injection).

Now, how does all of these individual stages communicate and know when to do what? The upper part of the launch vehicle has the Instrumentation Unit. Together with the Command Module, the Instrumentation Unit (IU) will take care of most of the sequencing and logic.
The IU will also control the entire rocket, unless you manually override the controls and give the controls to the Command Module Computer. This is only done during emergencies.

With all the major components out of the way, let's also take a look at the spacecraft itself. It has a few parts. The uppermost part is the Launch Escape Tower. It is used during an abort and will take the capsule away from the failing launch vehicle.
Once the capsule is above the atmosphere, the tower no longer has a use since other escape options must be used and is jettisoned automatically (default) or manually (emergency).
The Payload (Lunar Module) is located inside the S-IVB stage, inside the Spacecraft Lunar Module Adapter (SLA). It is protected by panels that is removed during S-IVB staging.
The service module will follow the Apollo capsule for almost the entire flight, and is separated just before reentry back to Earth.

Anyways, let's dive into the BOOST PREPARATION procedures. Use F12 to see the Mission Pad and follow the BOOS PREPARATION checklist. You can use the RUN feature that will use a marker to guide you through the steps that is in the worng configuration.
I will get back to you when we are a few minutes away from launch.
Two minutes to launch! Program 02 should now be running and is currently waiting for the umbilical disconnect signal.
Once the countdown reaches -00:09 seconds, the ignition sequence is starting. Prepare for a lot of vibrations at this time.
Once the ignition command is triggered, the engines will start to build up thrust. Once the thrust is nominal, the respective L/V ENGINES light will go out.
When all lights are extinguished, the eninges are performing normally. These should stay extinguished during the first two minutes.
The inboard engine (center light) will illuminate indicating the inboard engine cutoff at +02:16 and will be extinguished until staging when all engines are cutoff.
After cutoff, the S-IC separation will be triggered and S-II will ignite all its engines. The engine lights will once again be extinguished, indicating normal thrust.
One minute to launch. Once you have liftoff, there are three immediate things you need to check.
First is that the five engine lights are extinguished, then check that the computer switches to P11 and is displaying data (else press ENTR to committ the V75E command).
Lastly, check that the Mission Elapsed Time just under the warning lights panel on the top of MDC-2 starts counting up from zero.
Liftoff - as indicated by the LIFTOFF light on MDC-1 where the 8 glass-covered pushbuttons are, the top left one.
Check if engines are thursting, the computer is running P11 and that the clock has started.
The LV GUIDANCE has completed a small YAW maneuver to clear the tower, then a roll maneuver to tilt into the programmed direction.
The pitch program is running to pitch into orbit.
Abort MODE IA is complete, and MODE IB has started. There are a few abort modes, each with different abort procedures. These can be read in details in the manual.
Set the PRPLNT DUMP on MDC-2 to RCS CMD, in-case of an abort.
Monitor qa frequently while passing the atmoshere now, until +00:02 MET (mission elapsed time). The cabin pressure should be decreasing at 2.3 nautical miles altitude.
The computer is displaying some data. Register 1 (R1) is displaying VI (Inertial Velocity), R2 is displaying H dot, the altitude rate and R3 is displaying H pad (altitude above pad radius)
MAX Q, this is the point of the maximum dynamic pressure.
Entering abort MODE IC.
Set EDS AUTO to OFF
Set 2 ENG OUT to OFF
Set LV RATES to OFF
Inbord engine cutoff, indicated by the illumination of the center LV ENGINE light. All will illuminate soon when we stage.
S-IC/S-II Staging and separated, S-II engine ignition.
The tower will be jettisoned next and will fire its jettison engines to clear the spacecraft. This happens automatically but can be perfomed manually as well.
Tower is jettisoned.
Set the a/Pc switch to Pc, on MDC-1.
Set MAN ATT PITCH to RATE CMD.
Abort MODE II has started.
Set the four GIMBAL MOTOR switches on MDC-1 to START.
GIMBAL MOTOR PITCH 2 to START.
GIMBAL MOTOR YAW 1 to START.
GIMBAL MOTOR YAW 2 to START.
IECO, inboard engine cutoff
MODE IV
Stage II separation, S-IVB ignition.
SI-B will now thrust the final bit to orbit and automatically cut off at the right time. After this we will have to check the achieved orbit and do the insertion checklist.
Insertion into Earth Parking Orbit (EPO).
Write down the data from the registers: VI (R1), H dot (R2) and H pad (R3).
Key Rel is flashing on the computer. This means it wants to display data. To release the keyboard and let the computer control it again, press the KEY REL button on the DSKY.

The computer now displays the initial orbit. The guidance vehicle is still in early development, and as with the real rocket, the achieved orbit can be different. What we need to check now is that the Orbit is OK, meaning not dangerous.
Take a note of the data: R1 is displaying Ha (Apogee altitude), R2 is displaying Hp (Perigee altitude) and R3 is displaying the Time of free fall to 49.4 NM (300k ft).
If the orbit is safe, you can Key V37E 00E to let the computer run the idling Program 00.
Now that we are in orbit, we need to perform the post-insertion checklist. Insertion is mainly about turning off things we did during boost, and the things we need active during this initial orbit.
Let's learn about the interactive checklist feature. Press F12 or M to bring up the Mission Pad. Select CHECKLISTS and then INSERTION.
Read the entire checklist to become familiar with it, then press RUN. Closer the MISSION PAD using F12 or M and then follow the highlighter.
This concludes the boost lesson. Press ESC and END SESSION to return to main menu.

Title: Apollo Lesson 2 - Boost & Ascent
